@node Prefswindow
@{b} The Preferences Window.@{ub}

@{" BothImages   " link bothimages} | @{" The Save Path " link savepath}
@{" Icon names   " link iconnames} | @{" The ICON Path " link iconpath}
@{" Auto packing " link autopacking} | @{" The Rmke Path " link remakepath}
@{" Save packing " link savepacking} |
@{" Full windows " link fullwindows} |

@{" Save   " link saveprefs}@{" Use    " link useprefs}@{" Cancel " link cancelprefs}@{" Fill Col " link fillcol}

All user selectable preferences are activated from this window.

@endnode
@node fullwindows
@{B}Full Windows.@{ub}

If your workbench screen is taller than 256 pixels high, ie a DBLPAL or
an interlace screenmode, IdB gives you the choice of whether to have a
full screenheight window, or a half screenheight window, when viewing a
database.

Having a full height view window is more often useful when you just wish
to view a database. However, if you wish to install an icon then a half
height window would be more useful, because it would give you some space
on your workbench to arrange windows in.

@endnode
@node remakepath
@{B}The ReMake path.@{ub}

This path is used when you wish to `remake' a directory of icons from
IdB.

Remaking a directory consists of selecting a `Root category' from the
Root window. When selected then click on the Remake button and a
directory named after the selected `Root Category' will be created in
the selected `ReMake path'.

See:
@{" ReMake " link rootsrch}
@endnode

@node bothimages
@{b}Displaying Both Images.@{ub}

When displaying images, IdB is capable of showing both images in an icon
(assuming that the icon contains two images - most do.)

The initial state is single image display. This allows more icons to be
displayed in the viewing windows.

The `bothimages' button acts like a toggle.

@endnode
@node iconnames
@{b}Displaying the icon name.@{ub}

When displaying images IdB is capable of printing the icon name
underneath the icon image (as workbench does).

Initially this is set off. Pressing the button once will activate this
feature.

@endnode
@node savepacking
@{b}SavePacking.@{ub}

To help conserve storage space IdB is capable of packing it's save file.

To activate `save packing' just press this button.

Please note that the @{b}@{" XPK " link XPK}@{ub} program and the @{b}xpkNUKE@{ub} sub
library must be installed for this feature to function. 
@endnode
@node autopacking
@{b}AutoPacking.@{ub}

To help conserve memory in low memory situations IdB is capable of
individually packing all the icons in the computers memory.

Please note this really is only useful on low memory systems as it will
slow down all viewing operations, as all the icons will be unpacked as
required.

To activate `save packing' just press this button.

Please note that the @{b}@{" XPK " link XPK}@{ub} program and the @{b}xpkNUKE@{ub} sub
library must be installed for this feature to function. 

@endnode

@node savepath
@{b} The SAVE path.@{ub}

The save path specifies where IdB will save and load its database files
to.

The path can be selected by clicking on the button to the right of the
string gadget.

@endnode
@node iconpath
@{b} The ICON path.@{ub}

This path specifies where you keep your icon collections. If like me you
have (had) a lot of different icon collections you probably keep them in
one drawer. Set the ICON path to this drawer and it will help speed up
the icon adding process.

The path can be selected by clicking on the button to the right of the
string gadget.

@endnode
@node saveprefs
@{b}SAVE.@{ub}

Clicking on this button will save the current prefs settings. these
settings will then be used every time you reload IdB.

@endnode
@node useprefs
@{b}USE@{ub}

Clicking on this button will set the current prefs but will not save
them allowing you to temporarily use a different setup.

@endnode
@node cancelprefs
@{b}CANCEL@{ub}

This exits the preferences window.

@endnode
@node fillcol
@{b}The window fill colour.@{ub}

To make IdB look a little different I decided to give you the user the
chance to select which colour in which to display parts of the windows.

Clicking on this button brings up a palette requester. Simply click on
the colour you wish to become the fill colour then click on ` OK '.

If you wish to disable the fill colour click on the first colour 
(colour 0).

You can also modify the current palette from here, if you wish to
experiment and see how a different colour scheme affects the appearence
of your workbench.

@endnode


@node Load
@{b}Loading an IdB Database.@{ub}

This is from where you load a previously created Idb datafile!

Simply select the appropriate file from the the file requester.  If the
file is packed it will be decrunched when loading.

If you run out of memory while unpacking a database file, you could try
assigning @{b}T:@{ub} to somewhere on your harddrive.

T: is used to create a temporary unpacked file.

@endnode

@node Save
@{b}Saving an IdB Database.@{ub}

This is where you create an IdB datafile.

Simply select a suitable file name and use the file requester as usual.

IdB will suggest the filename IconBase.data, if you are just going to
have just one datafile then use this!

If `savepacking' is ON then the file will be crunched to save on disk
space.

@endnode

@node Add
@{b}Adding Icons to IdB.@{ub}

From here you can add either a single icon or a complete drawer full of
icons to IdB.

An initial file requester will appear, you can select an individual
`.info' file or by shift-selecting, select a number of .info's.
Clicking `ALL' in the file requester will automatically select all the
.info's in the current directory.

Clicking on ` OK ' will then close the file requester and start the
sequence of adding the icons to IdB.

Another window will then appear.  This window allows you to set the 2
description strings for the later referencing of your icons.

You can describe an icon in IdB in two ways.  The first is a generic
`ROOT' description that describes the overall collection or drawn-style
of an icon, eg.  @{" RomIcons " link RomICONS}, @{" MagicWb " link MAGICWB} or @{" IconoGfx " link ICONOGFX} 
are just some examples.  The second way of describing an icon is a
method of allocating `Icon categories' to an individual icon.  For
example a game or a def_icon, this is done by using IdB's category
system.

Briefly, the category system used by IdB is a 32 category bit
selectable system that allows you to allocate a number of categories to
an individual icon.  When you wish to view some icons later, you can
then specify which icons you want to see.  For example, all the game
icons or all the drawer icons you have in the IdB database.

See @{" Define Categories " link definecats} for more information on
categories.

Initially the window will contain the file path to the currently
selected icons, split into two strings.  This allows some automation of
the category setting.

The `ROOT' string will be set as the filepath, excluding the device
name, upto the last `/'.

The `Auto Category' string will be the remnant of the file path after
the last `/' character.

An Example:

Suppose you have a collection of @{" RomIcons " link RomICONS} stored in
WORK:Icons/RomIcons9 and you wish to add a collection of image drawers
stored in the sub-directory /Drawers to IdB.

Pointing the file requester to WORK:Icons/RomIcons9/Drawers and
selecting all the .infos will bring up the following description strings.

The `Root' description will be `Icons/RomIcons9'.  The `Auto Category'
description will be `drawers'.

Editing the `Root' description to just `RomIcons9' will then set the
description string correctly.
@{b}
IMPORTANT:
The `Root' description will remain the current root description until
you change it. If you wish to set it to the current path click on the 
` <> ' button to the right of the string gadget.@{ub}

The `Auto Category' description will be checked against the current
category definitions and if a match is found the appropriate category
will then be set for the current icons you are adding.

This method of parsing the filepath should allow for the quicker setting
of entire collections' categories, if you organize your icons-storage
well.

@{b}
NEW and IMPORTANT:
You can now use an alternative method of automatically setting the
default categories.

Clicking on the ` /\ ' button to the right of the string gadget will
open a window, almost identical to the select view window, wherby you
can select a number of categories to become the default categories.
@{ub}

A better explanation would just be try it and see!

After both strings have been set click on the ` OK ' button and another
window will then open and the icons will be processed one at a time.

@{i}That's all there is to it!  Believe me it's easier than it sounds.@{ui}

@endnode

@node view
@{b}Viewing Icons in an IdB File.@{ub}

After selecting `view' a window appears from where you can specify which
icons to view.  You can choose to view all the icons present in the
database or all the icons that have not been categorised yet or you can
choose an individual category or multiple categories to view.

To view ALL the icons in the database simple click on the ` ALL '
button.

To view the uncategorised icons select the ` UnCat ' button.  Useful
when you want to manually set the categories.

To select a category to view simply click on your desired category and
then on the ` Done ' button.

You can view more then one category at a time by selecting multiple
categories then clicking the `Done' button.

When viewing commences, the icons will appear in windows.  There may be
several windows overlapping if a large number of icons are to be viewed.

To minimise the number of open windows when viewing a large selection of
icons have the `Both images' preferences not set.

@{b}IMPOTANT:
Viewing a large amount of icons can use up a large portion of memory.
It is recommended that if you wish to view ALL the icons in the current
database, set both the `icon names' and `both images' flags (in the
preferences window) to off. This will then allow only an individual
image of the icon to be displayed.@{ub}

Clicking on an icon will bring up a new control window from where you
can perform several actions:

Action:
@{" Install        " link Install}
@{" Set categories " link SetCatagories}
@{" Delete         " link Delete}
@{" Icon Info      " link IconInfo}
@{" Save Icon      " link saveicon}
@{" Cancel         " link Cancel}
@{b}
Another feature can be accessed by pressing `Shift+p'. This will start a
palette requester in which you can alter the current palette. This may
be useful if you wish to see how a particular colour change can effect a
range of differnet icons.
@{ub}
@endnode

@node definecats
@{b}Define Categories.@{ub}

The category system in Idb is the heart of the viewing operations.
Defining an icon as being of certain categories will allow you to
organize and later view your icon collection in an efficient manner.

IdB allows you to define 32 categories.  A default category file comes
with IdB which should be satisfactory for most users, however, feel free
to alter it.  Bare in mind though, that there is only one category file
for all your possible databases, so you should decide on the category
definitions before you start creating databases.

To define a category just click into the relevant gadget and edit the
text to whatever you wish.

Please note that you can type in more than one word to represent a
certain category.

For example, an icon representing a harddrive might be stored in a
collection in a drawer named "Disks" or in a drawer named "Volumes",
perhaps even in "Devices".  To aid IdB when adding icons and
auto-categorising you could define ONE category as "DISKS VOLUMES
DEVICES", this would the allow IdB to automatically set the category
correctly if the icon is stored in any of the above directories.

@Endnode

@node rootsrch
@{b}Searching for a collection of icons.@{ub}

Clicking on this button will bring up a `listview' containing all the
`root-descriptions' of the icons in the current database.

Selecting one of these, just click on a name in the window, and then
clicking the search button will start the view operation, but only
displaying the icons that match the selected `root-description'.

This is useful to view a complete collection of icons, eg:  @{"RomIcons5 " link RomICONS},
in one go.

The @{b}`ReMake'@{ub} button is used to save out a complete set of icons
that match the selected `Root Description'. A path requester will appear
asking you to specify a place to extract the icons to. A directory with
the name of the selected `Root Description' will be made in this path,
and then all the icons that match this `Root Description' will be saved
as standard .info files.

The @{b}`DELETE'@{ub} button must be used with great care. It will
delete, from the current database, all icons that match the selected
`Root Description'.

@endnode

@node namesrch
@{b}Searching for an icon by a name.@{ub}

Simply type in the name, eg:  DPaint, that you wish to search for and
any icons with that name, or containing that name will then be
displayed.

DOS wildcard charcaters are now allowed (eg. #? and ?). If no wildcard
characters are entered into the search string then a case insensitive
INSTR search will be made.

For example, entering `Paint' would find DPAINT, Dpaint4, PPAINT and
DPAINT4Aga.

@endnode

