@node Install
@{b}Install@{ub}

From here you can copy an icon from IdB's current database to any file
using a drag'n'drop approach.

A window will open with 2 boxed areas and 2 buttons:

-------------------------------------------
| ------------------- ------------------- |
| |                 | |                 | |
| |                 | |                 | |
| |                 | |                 | |
| |                 | |                 | |
| |                 | |                 | |
| |                 | |                 | |
| |                 | |                 | |
| |                 | |                 | |
| ------------------- ------------------- |
| |     INSTALL     | |     CANCEL      | |
-------------------------------------------

The left hand box will contain the icon you have just selected in the
VIEW window.  Initially the right hand box will be `hashed out'.

To install this icon firstly click on install then simply move an icon
from workbench or any window open on workbench onto the right hand side
box.  The icon will then automatically replace the original icon.

No tooltypes will be altered.  All the original icon's information will
be preserved.

You can install an icon to a number of files be shift-selecting icons
and while holding down the shift key drop them on the righthand box.

To view the replaced icons use the `Update Window' menu item from the
workbench.

If anybody knows how to automatically refresh a window open on the
workbench from a BLitz2 program will you let me know please!

Pressing `Cancel' will close the Installation window and return you to
the `View' window.
 
@endnode 
@node SetCatagories 
@{b}Setting an Icons categories.@{ub}

To set the categories to reference an icon by, simply click on the
relevant buttons.

More then one category can be set for each individual icon.

@endnode 
@node Delete 
@{b}Deleting an Icon@{ub} 

Be careful with this!

Clicking this button will mark an icon as deleted from the database
file.  There is no undelete function!

Use to remove duplicate or unwanted icons.

@endnode 
@node Iconinfo 
@{b}Displaying Information About the Current Icon.@{ub} 

This section is in it's infancy, it will be made fully usable in the
next version.  At the moment it will only allow you to read various
pieces of information stored in an icon, it's ToolTypes and DefaultTool
for example.

@endnode 
@node cancel 
@{b}Cancel@{ub}

Hitting this button merely closes the Action window and allows you to
select another icon.

@endnode
