@node screens
@{b}Of Screens and Colours@{ub}

Running IdB on an OS3 machine (essential) you may experience difficulty
seeing different icon collections in their correct colours.  For example
MagicWb and IconGfx both use 8 colour screens but a different palette.

I have tried various methods trying to gain a perfect solution.  The
solution I personally use is the excellent LockColors by Torgier Hovden.

I run this program on a 64 colour workbench with the supplied config
file and all icons appear to work ok, appearing in their correct
colours.

You must also set the default palette to the following values:

Colour R   G   B
  0   149 149 149 (For a brighter background try 170 170 170)
  1     0   0   0
  2   255 255 255
  3    59 103 162
  4   255 176   5
  5     0  76 162
  6     0 204   0
  7   255  85  85 

This palette with the supplied Lockcolours config file will allow you to
use MagicWb, MagicWB2 (16 cols), IconoGfx, NewIcons and RomIcons (both 8
and 16 cols) on the same screen and appear in their correct colours.

LockColors can be found in the extras drawer in this distribution.

LockColors is copyright 1994 Torgier Hovden.

Note:  If MagicWb icons still appear in the wrong colours make sure that
they are only 3 bitplanes deep.  This can be achieved using the Opticon
program by Tobias Ferber, also available in the extras drawer.

@endnode
@node requirements
@{b}IdB Requirements.@{ub}

IdB requires OS3.0 and above. It will run happily on a 2MB machine, but
the more memory the better. A harddrive is also highly reccomended if
not quite essential.

If you are going to use databases of, say, 300 or more icons, then to
display them all with both images and icon names is going to require
more memory. Around 4mb should be ample.

The only library it requires is the reqtools library, which all users
should have this by now.

@endnode
@node aboutIDB
@{b} The About Window.@{ub}

This merely displays the copyright information as well as the version
of IdB. Some information regarding memory availability (the largest
chunks free in both chip and fast), and the number of icons in the
current database is also displayed.

@endnode

