@node example
@{b}About the Example Database.@{ub}

This  is just a small database containing icons that I have converted to
16 colours.

The were originally part of the ROMICONS1 and ROMICONS2 packages, but
converted to 16 colours by me.

Due to copyright, I suspect that I cannot supply all the icons
in IdB format that I have, so you will have to make do with just this
set for now. I haven't had the time to create any original icons or to
do anymore 16 colour conversions, since I have been working flat out for
months now trying to get IdB completed.

If any icon creators out there use IdB then, if you want, you could send
me a copy of them in IdB format and they will, space permitting, be
supplied on an examples disk with IdB.

@endnode

@node saveicon
@{b}To Save an Individual Icon.@{ub}

Clicking on the `Save Icon' button will save the current icon as a .info
file. A file requester will appear asking you to specify where you wish
this icon to be saved.

@endnode

@node BUGS
@{b}Undocumented features.@{ub}

If you find any bugs could you please write to me detailing what you
found. A description of your hardware setup would also be necessary.

Code:
MD      A bug that I've found.

MD Delete root. NOT FIXED YET.
   If the second icon in a database is in the root description that you
   wish to delete - it won't.     
   
   To get around this, delete the root normally then in the view window
   delete the individual icon.

This is not a bug in the program but in the reqtools library that blitz
uses:

I've had to put in a standard Blitz2 filerequester in the save icons
section. This is due to the RTEZSaveFile command not working correctly,
it appears to insert a null byte in the save file name cutting short the
filename. I know that the filename$ should be at least 108 characters
long, but, setting Maxspace filename$ 108 does not work. Setting the
filename$ to a string of 108 chars stops the bug but you then have to
clear the file requester savename gadget before you can type anything!
If anyone can help - PLEASE!

@endnode
